{"title": "The Omniscient", "content": "Janet: I'm Janet. I'm the informational assistant here in the Good Place. \n\nChidi: She's like this walking database. You can ask her about the creation of the universe or history... \n\nEleanor: Oh, there was a guy who lived in Avondale, Arizona, around 2002. His name was Kevin Paltonic. Is he gay? \n\nJanet: No. \n\nEleanor: Really? Huh. I guess he just didn't want to have sex with me. \n\nJanet: That's correct. \n\nEleanor: Well, that's fine, I wasn't that into him anyway. \n\nJanet: Yes, you were. I'm Janet. I'm the informational assistant here in the Good Place.She's like this walking database. You can ask her about the creation of the universe or history...Oh, there was a guy who lived in Avondale, Arizona, around 2002. His name was Kevin Paltonic. Is he gay?No.Really? Huh. I guess he just didn't want to have sex with me.That's correct.Well, that's fine, I wasn't that into him anyway.Yes, you were.\n\nA character that knows everything. Either literally everything, or simply everything worth knowing under the circumstances. May or may not have Blue and Orange Morality or a Omniscient Morality License. Not to Be Confused with a character who incorrectly believes himself to know everything. May or May not have authored the Great Big Book of Everything.\n\nBeings with this ability tend to be background characters that the reader is told little about. This is because \"knowing everything\" is a Story-Breaker Power, because it's difficult to feature a protagonist that can see all the cards, take action based on that knowledge, and maintain a sense of meaningful conflict. Another way to try to keep the story or interesting is to keep the readers/viewers in the dark about what the main character is truly doing and why, while the character executes a Gambit Pileup. (See Unspoken Plan Guarantee.) A final solution is to reveal that they are Not So Omniscient After All.\n\nThe Omniscient usually appears as an oracle (mad or otherwise), and/or leader of The Omniscient Council of Vagueness.\n\nFor The Omniscient to face a Moral Dilemma without becoming an Omniscient Hero, the dilemma has to remain very abstract. In philosophy, many thought-experiments are based on the outright or implied premise \"What would The Omniscient do?\"\n\nThis trope often overlap with The Omnipresent, since being omnipresent is often the reason why one is omniscient to begin with. The Omnipotent may have this as well.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheOmniscient?from=Main.Omniscience", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheGoodPlace", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/BlackParadox", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/XxxHOLiC", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Genshiken", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/VampireKnight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MagiLabyrinthOfMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/DarkerThanBlack", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MedakaBox", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/Baccano", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/PuellaMagiMadokaMagica", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/PuellaMagiMadokaMagicaTheMovieRebellion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Bleach", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/DragonBallSuper", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/ElfQuest", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/TheIncredibleHercules", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/MarvelComics", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/ChaosWar", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/EarthX", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/MyLittlePonyFriendshipIsMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Disney/Hercules", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Lucy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/TheMatrix", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MenInBlack3", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Thor", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ThorTheDarkWorld", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheMothmanProphecies", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/AstralDawn", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/CradleSeries", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Discworld", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/DavidEddings", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Malloreon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheDresdenFiles", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/L